a1350 33
     Any   figure   may   attempt   to   attack    a
hostile figure by  using  his  hands  and  feet.  For
many  monsters,  this  is  the  only  way  they   may
attack.    Unless    specified     otherwise,     all
figures/monsters    receive    one    attack     with
their    hands/claws/bite    per    Pulse     without
penalty.  Some  monsters   may   be   able   to   at-
tack  more   than   once,   and   these   individuals
are  detailed  in  the  Monsters  Section  (VI   11).

     For  a  humanoid  figure  to  strike  with  his
primary  hand,   the   Base   Chance   is   (modified
Agilityx2).   For   every    point    the    figure's
Physical   Strength   is   above   15,    the    Base
Chance  is  increased   by   1.   The   damage   done
by a successful  strike  is  D  -  4,  with  I  extra
point    of    damage    for    every    3     points of
Physical  Strength   above   15.   A   humanoid   can
achieve  Rank  with  bare  hands  just  as   he   can
with any weapon.

     Beginning at Rank   3    in    Unarmed    Com-
bat,  figures  may  choose   to   kick   insteadofus-
ing hands (or in addition to hands) in unarm-
ed  attack.   This   allows   an   unarmed   attack
while  a  figure's  hands  are   full.   The   Base
Chance  and  damage  are  as  above.   Using   legs
in this manner allows an attempted Trip . y
the attacker (see  16.5)  with  Base  Cha,,,e  a  d
damage  remaining  the  same  as  for  all   unarm-
ed combat.

22.  MULTI-HEX  MONSTERS
d1354 26
a1379 39
     Many  monsters   detailed   in   the   Monsters
Section  (VIII)  will  occupy  more  than  one  hex
on  the  Tactical  Display.  Their   size   necces-
     sitates the following  alterations  in  the  resolu-
     tion of movement and combat.

          Multi-hex  monsters   have   three   types   of
     hexes   surrounding   them:   Front,    Rear,    and
     Flank.  Front  and  Rear  hexes  function   in   the
     same  way  for  them  as  for  any   other   figure,
     but  attacks  through  Flank   hexsides   give   the
     attacker  a  bonus  (see  17.6).  The   exact   con-
     figuration  of  Front,   Rear,   and   Flank   hexes
     vary with the size of  the  monster  (see  illustra-
     tion).

          A   multi-hex   monster    must    always    be
     placed  on  the   display   such   that   its   head
     unambiguously   faces   a   vertex   of   two   hex-
     sides. It may move in  any  way  so  that  its  head
     enters any  Front  hex,  and  may  move  up  to  its
     full  TMR  in  this  fashion.  At  the  end  of  its
          ovement,   it   must   once   again    unambiguous-
     iy face a vertex.  For  facing  changes,  a  penally
     of one  less  hex  of  movement  for  each  two  hex
     e tices  changed  is   applied,   since   the   mass
     i)eing   maneuvered   is   much   greater   than   a
     humanoid's.  In  order   to   change   facing,   the
     monster must pivot  using  its  head  as  the  pivot
     point.

A  multi-hex  monster  may   freely   pivot   or
     7iove into any hex occupied by a I-hex
     figure. The smaller figure is knocked prone
     automatically  and  the  monster   may   then   at-
     tempt to  trample  the  figure  at  a  Base  Chance
     of  4007o,  doing  (DIO+size  of  the  monster   in
     exes)    damage.    Trampling    is     Class     C
                   aamage.
d1381 1
a1381 1
   See illustrations on this page and 22.
d1385 37
a1421 54
          in mounted combat, the TMR of     the
     figure  (comprising  the  mount  and   the   rider)
     is that of  the  mount;  the  rider  may  not  move
at  all.  A  rider  may  only  mount   or   dismount
when  the  mount  is  not  moving.  Any   action   a
figure  is  capable  of  while   standing   on   the
ground  he  is  capable   of   while   moun(ed   wih
the  following  exceptions:  (1)  using   a   t'A-0-
handed   weapon;   (2)   firing   any   missile   or
thrown  weapon  while   moving;   (3)   using   more
than  one  weapon  at  a  time.  These  restrictiors
are   lifted   depending   on    the    Horsemansh;-
Rank of the rider (see 83.2). A figure m
always  use  a  shield  and  a  one-handed  weapor',
while mounted.

The horseman with  the  sword  can  attack  into  hcx
A or hex C, but not into heX B. Thus, the figure  or.
foot cannot be hit with the sword, but  he  could  be
trampled.

     A  rider  and   mount   will   normally   occupy
only  one  hex,  unless  the  mount  is  a  multi-hex
monster.  If  they  occupy   more   than   one   hex,
the  movement  will  be  governed   biy   the   rules
of  multi-hex  monsters  (see  22).   On   a   normal
mount, the rider will  not  be  able  to  attack  out
of his Front hex, only the hexes to either  side
of that hex.  His  Front  hex  may  be  attacked
into using  a  spear  (or  similar  long  hafted
weapon) or any Fired weapon (see  illustration).

     To  control  a  mount  during  combat,   the
Horsemanship skill of the rider  is  taken  into
account.   An   inexperienced   horseman    will
have an  incredibly  difficult  time  even  con-
trolling his mount in a chaotic melee;  it  will
be @@,etter for him  to  dismount  and  fight  on
foot until hc becomes skilled.

     A Charge on  a  mount  is  executed  in  the
same manner as  a  Charge  on  foot  except  the
amount of movement  prior  to  the  attack  will
be  greater  and  the  Charge  must  be   in   a
straight line (no facing changes allow         1.
Any act of turning the mount or stopping it
during or after the Charge will require a
Horsemanship  Check  (see   82.2).   The   Pulse
following  any  mounted   Charge,   the   momen-
tum will take the mount past the target to  its
full TMR. Any  attempt  to  turn  or  stop  the
mount will occur after that  movement  is  ter-
minated. A failed  check  will  result  in  the
mount continuing on its way.
d1426 26
a1451 36
     At the end  of  every  combat  in  which  a
figure  is  wounded,  or  when  a   figure   is
wounded in a  non-combat  situation,  there  is
the possibility  that  figure  has  become  in-
fected as a result of his wound.  An  Infection
Check   must   be   performed   to    determine
whether he is infected or not.

     The Base Chance of infection  is  equal  to
1001o. If the figure took  any  damage  to  En-
durance, add (20  +  the  amount  of  Endurance
damage  in  points).  If  the  damage  was  in-
flicted by bite,  claws,  or  talons,  add  20.

Specific Grievous Injuries  may  raise  the  Base
Chance  even   further.   The   infected   figure
rolls DIOO; if the result  is  greater  than  the
modi@@  Base  Chance,  the  figure  is   not   in-
fected; if the result is equal to or  less  than,
the rigurc is infected.

     An infected  figure  is  considered  diseas-
ed,  and  every  morning   after   becoming   in-
fected, the figure must try to  heal  himself  or
suffer  Endurance  damage.  To  heal  himself,  a
figure  ires  to  roll  under  his  original  En-
durance on DIOO; a roll equal  to  or  less  than
the Endurance results in a cure.  If  the  infec-
tion is not cured,  each  day  the  figure  takes
DIO-5   (minimum   result   of    1)    Endurance
damage from  the  infection.  Obviously,  an  in-
fected figure who is not  cured  will  eventually
die from his wounds.  The  effects  of  slow  ac-
ting  (blood  agent)  poisons  function  in   the
same manner as  infections  except  there  is  no
roll for cure.
